  "outputText": "The user wants an explanation of why three specific metrics (prefill throughput, decode throughput, TTFT) are necessary for evaluating LLM serving systems. I need to break down each metric's meaning and what it reveals about system performance.\n\nPrefill vs. decode is the fundamental distinction in transformer inference: prefill processes the entire prompt in parallel; decode generates one token at a time (autoregressive). These two phases have different compute/memory patterns, so conflating them into a single throughput number hides important information.\n\nTTFT = Time to First Token. This is what users actually experience as latency for chat applications — how long they wait before the response starts appearing. It's dominated by prefill time (plus scheduling overhead). A slow TTFT makes an app feel unresponsive, even if later tokens come out fast.\n\nPrefill throughput measures how many prompt tokens per second the system can ingest. This matters for batching multiple requests and for long-context applications. High prefill throughput means you can handle more concurrent users with large prompts without queuing.\n\nDecode throughput is tokens generated per second across all active requests. For a single user, this determines reading speed (tokens/sec). For an operator, it's the aggregate system utilization —",
